allery","type":"image","galleryIndex":8,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939224980/The-British-Dream-by-Davi-005.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","photographer":"Picasa","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The British Dream by David Goodhart","height":"536","credit":"Picasa/PR","caption":"<strong>The British Dream by David Goodhart</strong> <br/>\r\nGoodhart's battle against the liberal establishment goes back at least to 2004, when he wrote a piece for Prospect magazine inspired by David Willetts's theory that welfare states only work in culturally homogenous societies (\"to put it bluntly\", Goodhart wrote, \"most of us prefer our own kind\") ... Now Goodhart has expanded his arguments for less immigration and more nationalism into The British Dream... David Goodhart is not exceptional in these views, and some of his ideas – like free English lessons for newcomers – are excellent. But The British Dream raises the question as to whether someone who believes in quite so much exclusion and compulsion is any kind of liberal. Not so much \"post\", you might say, as \"anti\". <br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/03/british-dream-david-goodhart-review\">• Read the full review here</a>","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939224980/The-British-Dream-by-Davi-005-thumb-6198.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","photographer":"Picasa","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The British Dream by David Goodhart","height":"68","credit":"Picasa/PR","caption":"The British Dream by David Goodhart","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433154629","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":9,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939222597/The-Confidence-Trap-by-Da-004.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The Confidence Trap by David Runciman","height":"600","credit":"PR","caption":"<strong>The Confidence Trap by David Runciman</strong> <br/>\r\nDemocracies develop confidence in their long-term resilience, based in part on their ability to adapt (in contrast with rigid autocracy). This confidence that all will end well leads democratic states to be complacent, allowing problems to fester, safe in the knowledge that, when it really counts, they'll solve them. Those problems eventually come to a head in the form of a grave crisis. But confronted with such a crisis, democracies usually do adapt just enough to survive. Confidence returns, which eventually turns into complacency and so it begins again. This is the confidence trap. Democracy, says Runciman, can never escape it. <br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/nov/15/confidence-trap-david-runciman-review\">• Read the full review here</a>","width":"398"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939222597/The-Confidence-Trap-by-Da-004-thumb-8336.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The Confidence Trap by David Runciman","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":"The Confidence Trap by David Runciman","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433154643","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":10,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939220302/The-General-by-Ahmed-Erra-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The General by Ahmed Errachidi","height":"600","credit":"PR","caption":"<strong>The General by Ahmed Errachidi</strong>: <br/>\r\nThere are two stories that are impossible to make proper sense of in Ahmed Errachidi's graphic and powerful memoir of his five years of illegal detainment and torture in Guantánamo Bay. The first, overriding one, is the cruel insanity of the regime of interrogation that he suffered, a never-ending nightmare of sleep deprivation and beatings and solitary confinement, which he endured with defiance and stubborn courage. The second, which nags just slightly throughout, is Errachidi's account of the bizarre personal decisions that led him to being incarcerated in the first place ... You are left feeling that there is no such thing as an \"ordinary man\", as the book's subtitle wants to describe him; another is that his extraordinary story, with all its surreal and brutal twists, needed telling. <br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/08/general-guantanamo-ahmed-errachidi-review\">• Read the full review here</a>","width":"397"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939220302/The-General-by-Ahmed-Erra-003-thumb-1325.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The General by Ahmed Errachidi","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":"The General by Ahmed Errachidi","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433154645","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":11,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939240678/The-Tragedy-of-Liberation-011.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The Tragedy of Liberation by Frank Dikötter","height":"600","credit":"PR","caption":"<strong>The Tragedy of Liberation by Frank Dikötter</strong> <br/>\r\nFor many years, historians tended to argue that the first decade or so of [Mao's] rule was generally benevolent and productive, with the rot setting in during the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution. Dikötter takes a significantly different stance: the state was from its foundation shaped by violence and used coercion, both psychological and physical, to exert its will on the population. This version of the People's Republic of China is not a paradise lost: it was always hell. <br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/aug/30/tragedy-liberation-frank-dikotter-review\">• Read the full review here</a>","width":"392"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939240678/The-Tragedy-of-Liberation-011-thumb-3000.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The Tragedy of Liberation by Frank Dikötter","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":"The Tragedy of Liberation by Frank Dikötter","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433154647","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":12,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939217889/The-Worlds-Most-Dangerous-002.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The World's Most Dangerous Place by James Fergusson","height":"600","credit":"PR","caption":"<strong>The World's Most Dangerous Place by James Fergusson</strong> <br/>\r\nJames Fergusson, freelance journalist and author of several books on the Taliban, has a talent for shedding light in dark places. None is darker, or more dangerous, in his view, than Somalia, the \"outlaw state\". While most reporters – and some two million Somalis – have opted to stay away, Fergusson has risked his life to cover the ground and, an even greater achievement, succeeded in making the Somali mess understandable and relevant. <br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/feb/04/most-dangerous-place-fergusson-review\">• Read the full review here</a>","width":"393"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395939217889/The-Worlds-Most-Dangerous-002-thumb-4510.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"The Orwell Prize Longlist: The World's Most Dangerous Pl