o Crawford's remark is just as interesting:</p><p></p><p><blockquote>\"No doubt one is familiar with Shakespeare in a degree ... from one's earliest years. His celebrated passages are quoted by everybody; they are in half the books we open, and we all talk Shakespeare, use his similes, and describe with his descriptions; but this is totally distinct from giving his sense as you gave it. To know him in bits and scraps is common enough; to know him pretty thoroughly is, perhaps, not uncommon; but to read him well aloud is no everyday talent.\"</blockquote></p><p></p><p>I won't pretend to be able to read Shakespeare well aloud. In fact, here's my confession. If you asked me, I'd probably say I know Shakespeare \"pretty thoroughly\", but the truth is that I haven't paid much attention to him for longer than I'd care to admit. I read a lot in my teens, a bit in my 20s, and hardly any in the last few years.</p><p></p><p>I'm guessing there must be plenty of other people out there in a similar position. So this 450th anniversary seems like a great excuse to get reacquainted with the great man. The only question is where to start. I know where to stop. Generally when inviting nominations for the Reading group, I suggest we could also look at writers and novels directly influenced by the main subject. But since, in Shakespeare's case, that means just about everything written in English after his death, let's not go there. Instead, let's focus only on the Bard himself. There are 38 (according to most people) plays to choose from, a whole bunch of sonnets, and a few narrative poems. Some of them are so good that they still seem like miracles, more than 400 years after they first arrived. All nominations will be gratefully received – and since we're sticking to one author, why don't we have a vote? Over to you.</p><p></p><p></p>","headline":"Choose April's Reading group: William Shakespeare","trailText":"He is the world's best-known writer – and perhaps one of its least read. On