onal experiences.\" It&nbsp;becomes apparent very fast why this book feels so long – no statement is too&nbsp;banal not to warrant saying at least once. Its core propositions are repeated many times. They run as follows: adolescent brain-growth is defined by&nbsp;four traits: novelty seeking, social engagement, increased emotional intensity, creative exploration. We can&nbsp;perceive these as threats to the adolescent's safety – which they often&nbsp;are, especially if the creative exploration involves, say, taking an E – and we can also see them as threats to&nbsp;our attachment and happiness, as they push us away. I'm approaching this, incidentally, as the hypothetical parent to whom the book is addressed, rather than the adolescent, whom it also seeks to engage; if I were an adolescent reading this, I would have set fire to it and hurled it into dry woodland, to express my rage and also&nbsp;to impress my friends.</p><p>Most immediately irksome, apart from the amateurish illustrations, are the paternalistic instructions in how this book should be read. \"You may want to experience the book in whatever approach is best for you after reading Part I … If you enjoy learning by blending concepts and facts with science and stories, reading the book from front to back might be best …\" What this means in practice is that the&nbsp;book does not progress from hypothesis, via evidence, to credible thesis, but rather, tosses out theses and half-theses and notions and fancies like a wise and kindly man feeding seed to birds.</p><p>Siegel considers at the outset why we should take seriously the proposition of supporting and nurturing adolescent changes, rather than fearing and rejecting them. \"With all the problems our world faces today … never before have we so desperately needed a way to think beyond our usual strategies to create innovative ways of sustainable living on our precious planet. My suggestion to you is that the power of the adolescent mind has just that spark of emotion and social drive, just that push to explore new solutions to old ways of doing things, that may save life&nbsp;on our planet.\"</p><p>I struggled somewhat with the meaning of this – is it that teenagers have solutions within them right now, the imagination and originality to avert&nbsp;the environmental apocalypse? Because if so, surely the last thing we should be doing is bending our own brains to make the effort to understand why they want to go to the shops with their friends when they already have all the eye shadow they need? Surely we should be putting them in some kind of hothouse where their ideas can&nbsp;really make a difference?</p><p>It's possible that he means something&nbsp;different – that adolescents treated with sensitivity now will retain enough of their optimism to become the adults that can solve our planetary problems. But this is also difficult to substantiate: why haven't the rest of&nbsp;us&nbsp;grown into these pro-social, intellectually ambitious adults? What grounds do we&nbsp;have to offload these burdens on to&nbsp;the next generation? I&nbsp;mean, I'm no sentimentalist, I'd certainly leave it to them if I thought they were up to it; but I see no reasonable grounds for believing that, however empathically we manage to&nbsp;treat them during their intensely flexible brain period.</p><p>But hey, it doesn't matter, apparently, because \"even if we don't buy into the idea that adolescents will save the world, at least understanding brain science may help explain how we can encourage a teen to decide to call home or come in by one in the morning instead of three.\"</p><p>If it's intended as bathos, this fails; the sombre mood created by the spectre of global scarcity isn't alleviated by the light-hearted, hackneyed kicker. Actually, I don't think Siegel does have that intention; I&nbsp;think these are all just seed, cast before us. \"You want to believe they'll save the world? They may! Or maybe you just want them to call once in a while? We can do that too!\"</p><p>And yet there is something else in his writing, some quality of patience and warmth. Sara, a patient (some names have been changed) was having&nbsp;trouble allowing her son his independence. \"To a certain extent, she had been relying on him as an attachment figure, as if he were a parent and she his young child. Of course this meant that his moving away for a year was absolutely terrifying. Sara needed to learn to soothe the 'younger Sara'…\" There is a&nbsp;gentleness and acceptance in his tone; it made me realise that there is more to this phenomenon (and the book has been extremely successful) than desperate parents who will read&nbsp;anything.</p><p>By exhibiting exactly the traits he counsels – humility and self-awareness, though he would call it the COAL toolkit (curiosity, openness, acceptance and love – don't get me started on the acronyms) – he neutralises the hostility that I (critics and adolescents being in this respect indistinguishable) would naturally exhibit.</p><p>So I may as well admit to finding some of his arguments appealing and even beautiful. He insists on the plasticity of the brain, the fact that it&nbsp;can change at any age, open itself up&nbsp;to&nbsp;different approaches, access different areas, always increase its power. His counsel has a determined, unswervable generosity: it insists that&nbsp;you do think about your own attachments, what fears of rejection or loss you might be masking, in the fears you think are for your children. Although the practical advice is the most repetitive area, it does speak of an intense, humane desire on&nbsp;the author's part to do more than promulgate ideas: to get his readers actively interrogating their own feelings, actively extending their own&nbsp;empathy, actively \"harmonising\" that process (his word), so that self‑examination isn't indulgent or isolating, but rather, is the beginning of&nbsp;honesty.</p><p>The book is an extension of <a href=\"http://www.drdansiegel.com/about/mindsight/\" title=\"\">Siegel's work on \"mindsight\"</a> – this process of&nbsp;insight, empathy and integration –&nbsp;explained in sentences that occasionally I don't understand. \"Information is when energy flow represents something … And this movement across time, this flow that we are saying is an aspect of the mind, is all about energy and information and&nbsp;how it changes across time.\" I&nbsp;remember someone's dad saying to me when I started university and was intimidated by a lecturer: \"I used to think when someone said something I didn't understand, that they were more intelligent than me. Now I just think they're not expressing themselves very well.\"</p><p>But even in remembering that to criticise him, I make Siegel's deeper point: that sensitive adults, who don't have to be parents, who talk to you honestly, who can see your distress and don't belittle it, who understand your point of view and put theirs in a way that doesn't patronise you – those people will stay with you for the rest of&nbsp;your life.</p>","headline":"Brainstorm review – 'How to cope with teenagers'","trailText":"Daniel J Siegel's bestselling exploration of the purpose and power of the teenage brain may not be thoroughly scientific in its approach, but it does make for an honest inquiry","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Books/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395769741335/human-brain.-Image-shot-2-004.jpg","wordcount":"1134","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-09T16:42:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/27/brainstorm-review-daniel-j-siegel-can-adolescent-brain-save-world","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/27/brainstorm-review-daniel-j-siegel-can-adolescent-brain-save-world","tags":[{"id":"books/scienceandnature","webTitle":"Science and nature","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/scienceandnature","apiUrl":"http://beta.co