s a \"redfish\". Not to mention the fact that the French for April’s fool is \"April’s fish\". So, just communicate all that, would you?<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nPS. Did I mention that \"April\" is a boy in the French? Just the small matter of our goldfish switching gender for her English incarnation, then.","width":"480"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999903465/Cover-008-thumb-6932.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Cover","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197591","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":2,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999901086/To-be-007.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: To be","height":"363","credit":"PR","caption":"I believe this is the first time, in my admittedly varied career as a translator, that I’ve been expected to render a Shakespeare quoting, pun-spouting, trans-gender goldfish with suicidal tendencies.<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nHere’s the rub. Hamlet’s most famous question would usually be translated into French as \"Etre ou ne pas être?\" But Marjolaine Leray wittily writes \"Etre ou arrête?\" – a visual pun on the verb to stop (arrêter) and the word for fishbone (arête). Which might explain why I chose to parachute in \"picked over\". (Although, I have to admit, my favourite freestyle translation here would be: \"Oh that this too, too solid fish…\" Translational, visual, punning heaven!) ","width":"760"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999901086/To-be-007-thumb-4966.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: To be","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197557","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":3,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999889435/Aquaholics-002.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Aquaholics","height":"403","credit":"PR","caption":"Sometimes it's not what you lose in translation, but what you gain by adding in. Marjolaine Leray draws April’s parent on the left hiccupping: ‘cul sec!’ (Literally: dry bottom – for downing a drink in one.) Visually, this works exquisitely with the goldfish’s nether parts sticking up out of the water – and it chimes pleasingly with the English equivalent of ‘Bottoms up!’ But I almost prefer the English version now, where we chose to give the parent on the right something drink-related to say (in the French, they’re silent). <br/><br/>\r\nThese variations between the English version and the original arise out of an intricate relationship with Marjolaine Leray as author-illustrator-creator. As our ideas ping across the Channel, she hand writes the English text (and then re-writes it, if we don’t feel the letters are clear enough for a young Anglophone readership) ahead of the book being physically born again in another language and another culture.","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999889435/Aquaholics-002-thumb-779.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Aquaholics","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197568","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":4,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999894198/Prawns-004.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Prawns","height":"385","credit":"PR","caption":"How free can a translation be? In the French, April staring through her goldfish bowl at a dodgy looking platter of parental sushi is captioned (literally): \"Since then, they’ve moved on to other things\".  Or, more idiomatically, \"they’ve moved on to pastures new.\" Except that pastures and fish don’t mix. Translator, beware! All roads lead to the mixed metaphor, unless you’re über-careful (see?).<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nBut back to the parental sushi. I was conscious that \"moving on to other things\" is hardly the punchiest of captions. And so I decided to let Marjolaine’s drawing be my guide. After all, I am serving two masters here – the words and the visuals. If the former won’t bale me out, the latter just might. With \"bitter taste\" I wanted to emphasize both the shift from fish to fodder; and the cruel impact of bereavement on April, as she struggles in her search for meaning.","width":"760"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999894198/Prawns-004-thumb-9373.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Prawns","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197575","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":5,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999898849/Suicide-006.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Suicide","height":"388","credit":"PR","caption":"Whether 'tis Nobler in the mind to suffer/The Slings and Arrows of outrageous Fortune. Or to take Arms against the PC police? Parents, teachers, librarians, booksellers, publishers, the children themselves…?  Who decides on what is or isn’t \"appropriate\" for young readers?  The spectre of invisible gatekeepers is often mentioned in relation to children’s titles. But, as anyone who’s ever opened a Roald Dahl book, or blocked their ears in a pantomime, knows, a small person’s appetite for the gory, the gruesome and the frankly macabre is primordial. As is their capacity to find the hilarious in the grotesque.<br/><br/>\r\n\r\nStill, there are those who might argue that April The Red Goldfish should carry a recommendation of parental guidance, plus a warning \"not to try this at home\".","width":"760"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999898849/Suicide-006-thumb-9834.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Suicide","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197573","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":6,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999896384/Punk-005.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Punk","height":"418","credit":"PR","caption":"Can you hear my audible sigh of relief? Sometimes, just for a nanosecond, a translator's life is easy!","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999896384/Punk-005-thumb-5310.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Punk","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197566","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":7,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999891677/Hitch-a-ride-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Hitch a ride","height":"388","credit":"PR","caption":"Across these two spreads I swashbuckled in translation as a creative act of writing, albeit with strict spatial constraints. Paradoxically, in response to those spatial constraints, I allowed myself free rein: on the basis that my task here is akin to that of an advertising creative, conjuring up a new caption to target an English audience. The French on the left hand spread reads (literally): He (remember, April’s a boy in the French) isn’t planning on setting off with someone; while the right hand spread reads: or on making an interior journey. \r\n<br/><br/>\r\nAgain, I took the drawings as my starting point, re-imagined the captions, and in so doing caged a negative statement as a positive question.","width":"760"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999891677/Hitch-a-ride-003-thumb-2946.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Hitch a ride","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433197555","relation":"gallery","type":"image","galleryIndex":8,"assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999886629/Aprils-fool-001.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Aprils fool","height":"409","credit":"PR","caption":"Hurray! At last I’ve found my chance to sneak in the April's Fool reference. Here, the French reads: \"and make him [the enemy] into his [April’s] pet animal.\" Out with pets and in with April’s fools, say I!<br/><br/>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9781907912405\">April the Red Goldfish</a> is published by Phoenix Yard Books. It was originally published in French in 2013 under the title Avril Le Poisson Rouge. Written by Marjolaine Leray and translated by Sarah Ardizzone.\r\n","width":"400"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1395999886629/Aprils-fool-001-thumb-5534.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"April the red goldfish: Aprils fool","height":"68","credit":"PR","caption":" ","width":"68"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Live webchat with SF writer and Philip K Dick fan Jeff VanderMeer","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-25T11:31:00Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/2014/mar/25/live-webchat-philip-k-dick-jeff-vandermeer","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nz32","standfirst":"Is there more to the bewildering Ubik than even Dick himself  would admit? Award-winning writer Jeff VanderMeer joined us to discuss this topic and more","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Philip K Dick's Ubik has definitely given us plenty to talk about on this month's reading group. Teasing out this book's many strands, influences and implications has been fascinating – and bewildering. What does it all mean? I'm still not sure. Maybe nothing, if you believe <a href=\"https://archive.org/details/ATalkWithPhilipK.DickOnHour25In1976\" title=\"\">what the author said</a> in 1976:</p><blockquote><p>\"You don't just write whatever comes into your head while you're sitting there in front of the typewriter. When I wrote UBIK, I got about 12 pages done and couldn't think of anything else, so l just wrote whatever came into my mind. I wrote it from my unconscious: I let the right hemisphere of my brain do all the thinking, and I was as surprised as anybody as to what came out. In France, of course, it's considered a great novel because it doesn't make any sense; in France, it's a r<em>oman de pataphysique</em>.\"</p></blockquote><p>Darn it! But the fact that all that complication and drama in Ubik may not add up to anything also enables it to add up to everything. It is a novel of infinite possibility. It's a bravura display of narrative uncertainty. And Dick is a master at holding his readers' attention while everything falls apart.</p><p>All of which makes me very pleased to announce that we're going to be joined by Jeff VanderMeer at 1pm on Friday 28 March for this month's live webchat. Anyone who has read VanderMeer's award-winning fiction – and especially his latest novel <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/05/annihilation-review-jeff-vandermeer-afraid-turn-page\" title=\"\">Annihilation</a> - will be aware that this writer also knows a thing or two about keeping his readers guessing. And since definite answers about Ubik are so hard to come by, it seems a good idea to alter our usual formula slightly and question someone who has an affinity for Dick's kind of writing as well as expertise on the author's life and times.</p><p>Annihilation is full of the unease and mystery that make Dick's books so fascinating – and notably, in fine Philip K Dick style – it was <a href=\"http://www.buzzfeed.com/lincolnmichel/jeff-vandermeer\" title=\"\">inspired by a dream</a>.  Judging by the buzz about the book, and the reviews its been getting, that was an excellent night's work.</p><p>I'm sure it's going to be intriguing to hear about the creation of this work, not to mention VanderMeer's influences, what he thinks of Dick himself and his opinions on the history of this kind of speculative fiction. Although we have invited Jeff primarily as a creative artist, it's also worth noting that he's no slouch on this latter subject, having co-edited a number of highly respected SF anthologies such as <a href=\"http://www.jeffvandermeer.com/2011/08/30/table-of-contents-the-weird-edited-by-ann-and-jeff-vandermeer/\" title=\"\">The Weird</a>. While I'm noting his qualifications, I should also say that he is the winner of two World Fantasy awards as well as a finalist for the Hugo awards and significantly, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_K._Dick_Award\" title=\"\">the Philip K Dick award</a>. (He has also chaired the panel of judges for the latter.) He was also the editor and publisher of <a href=\"http://www.jeffvandermeer.com/2012/07/01/cheeky-frawg-news-stepan-chapmans-pkd-award-winning-the-troika/\">The Troika by Stepan Chapman</a>, which won a PKD award and was very influenced by Philip K Dick and Ubik.</p><p>But really, I don't need to say much more to introduce Jeff VanderMeer because his words speak for themselves. You can <a href=\"http://io9.com/read-the-mesmerizing-first-chapter-of-jeff-vandermeers-1520682658\" title=\"\">read the first chapter of Annihilation here</a>. Better still, we have copies to give away to the first 10 people to post a relevant question, alongside \"I want a copy please\". And if you're lucky enough to get your request in quickly, don't forget to email <a href=\"mailto:laura.kemp@theguardian.com\" title=\"\">laura.kemp@theguardian.com</a> (Ginny is away for a couple of months) as we can't track you down ourselves – and don't forget to be nice!</p><p>Jeff will be here at 1pm on Friday – but please feel free to get your questions in early, and post now if you don't think you can make the allotted time. Over to you!</p>","headline":"Live webchat with SF writer and Philip K Dick fan Jeff VanderMeer","trailText":"<p><strong>Sam Jordison:</strong> Is there more to the bewildering Ubik than even Dick himself  would admit? Award-winning writer Jeff VanderMeer joined us to discuss this topic and more</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/24/1395683351183/Philip-K.-Dick-American-a-003.jpg","wordcount":"622","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-30T15:54:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/25/live-webchat-philip-k-dick-jeff-vandermeer","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/25/live-webchat-philip-k-dick-jeff-vandermeer","tags":[{"id":"books/series/reading-group","webTitle":"Reading group","type":"series","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/reading-group","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/series/reading-group","references":[]},{"id":"books/philipkdick","webTitle":"Philip K Dick","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/philipkdick","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/philipkdick","references":[]},{"id":"books/science-fiction","webTitle":"Scie