/static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/17/1395079407738/kim-philby-002.jpg","typeData":{"source":"PR","altText":"kim philby","height":"215","credit":"PR","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Bad mothers in books: a literary litany","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-27T08:30:00Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/2014/mar/27/bad-mothers-in-books-literature","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nq8y","standfirst":"As Mother's Day looms, we are surrounded by saintly images of perfect matriarchs. But what of the worst mums in fiction?","hasStoryPackage":"true","body":"<p>A quick glance at the racks of Mother's Day cards would turn anyone off motherhood: of course we love our mothers, but really – would we truly express it like that? And is there a faint feeling that the more extreme, gushing cards might be chosen by those whose relationships with their mothers are not, in fact, perfect? So it might be refreshing to take a turn round some imperfect parents in fiction: here we go with the bad mothers' literary litany.</p><p>Mrs Bennet from Jane Austen's Pride and Prejudice <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jan/26/pride-prejudice-200th-anniversary\" title=\"\">is always Exhibit A</a> – but her real crime seems to be that she embarrasses her sensitive children. Read it as a teenager and you wince for poor mortified Lizzie and Jane, thinking perhaps of times when our own mother said the wrong thing. The older reader – more robust, a parent – can think it is the positive duty and pleasure of a mother to embarrass her child from time to time, to stop them getting on their high horse. And, as apologists of Mrs B have pointed out, at least she is trying to do something about the family's woeful situation: she appreciates the poverty and misery that will face them all if marriages are not made. Perfect papa Mr B – so lovely, so witty at the expense of his family – appears not to give a toss about what will happen to his daughters.</p><p>Charles Dickens had an extremely difficult relationship with both of his parents – they were feckless, and he felt they let him down badly – and mothers do not come off well in the books. His picture of his own mother is Mrs Nickleby – mother to Nicholas and Kate – and is quite painful. She is incompetent, foolish, and no good in a sickroom – \"coming into the room with an elaborate caution, calculated to discompose the nerves of an invalid rather more than the entry of a horse-soldier at full gallop\" – very unhelpful given the amount of illness and nursing occurring in the oeuvre. Mrs Copperfield, horribly, fails to protect David from his stepfather, while Bleak House's Mrs Jellyby lets the children fall downstairs and get their heads stuck in railings because she is so busy with her charitable works.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/marilynne-robinson\" title=\"\">Marilynne Robinson</a>'s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/may/03/featuresreviews.guardianreview13\" title=\"\">Housekeeping</a>, Lucille and Ruth's mother commits suicide, leaving them to face an uncertain future. In Nick Hornby's About a Boy, the mother attempts suicide in a situation where the boy Marcus will find her and – much worse – cuts his hair for him (\"fashion is stupid, baa, sheep\"), part of what stops him fitting in at school.</p><p>The mother in Arthur Ransome's children's classic, Swallows and Amazons, is something of a cipher, but her inability to make basic decisions does mean she receives one of the finest telegrams in all literature. Asked if the children may go on an adventurous sailing-and-camping expedition, the absent father replies, heartlessly: \"Better drowned than duffers if not duffers will not drown.\"</p><p>In children's books of that era (the Ransome was published in 1930), parents are nearly always absent or dead in order to clear the decks for adventure and excitement, and in some adult books the same easy path is taken. The over-productive romance writer Ruby M Ayres gave us a very bad mother in her 1924 book Ribbons and Lace. The heroine, who changes her name to Linda Lovelace (yes really) is left to fend for herself and her grandmother when her father dies, leaving them penniless – the mother wanders off in search of a better life, although she does turn up again when there is some prospect of Linda marrying money. She is rotten through and through, as you feel Ayres might have put it herself.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-433070146'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Books/Pix/pictures/2011/8/24/1314179894456/Still-from-Channel-4s-The-007.jpg' alt='Still from Channel 4's The Illustrated Mum' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Compulsive viewing... The TV version of The Illustrated Mum. Photograph: Channel 4</figcaption></figure><p>In modern children's books, mothers are often just plain unsatisfactory. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/may/11/costabookaward.jacquelinewilson\" title=\"\">The Illustrated Mum</a> is one of Jacqueline Wilson's many examples (tattoos and bipolar disorder), while the parents of Roald Dahl's Matilda (the small person's Carrie) are splendidly grotesque. Mrs Wormwood chose \"looks not books\". Dahl knew what he was doing: to good middle-class parents, disapproving of reading is the worst mistreatment, worse than Barbie dolls and sweets.</p><p>There are spectacularly neglectful mothers in Philip Hensher's 2011 King of the Badgers, and in Dennis Lehane's thriller Gone Baby Gone (1998) – the Lehane ending on a decision concerning the mother that must have every reader (or viewer of the 2007 film) debating the rights and wrongs of the case. These are both very working-class women – but negligence crosses the boundaries. Lady Montdore in Love in a Cold Climate greets her only daughter after the death of her first child with \"So the poor little baby died, I expect it was just as well, children are such an awful expense\". The various mothers in Vita Sackville-West's The Edwardians (1930, looking back at pre-first world war days), are heartless and unable to understand their daughters, ready to marry them off to the highest bidder. One of the daughters in the book, in love with a penniless artist, is told by her mother's friend to marry the lord who is also on the scene and, with a hideous wink, \"we'll see what can be done about the painter afterwards.\"</p><p>Evelyn Waugh's Brenda Last (in the 1934 novel Handful of Dust) takes some kind of prize: her lover and her child are both called John, and when she is told \"John is dead\" she is relieved that it is the child. The main thought that this provokes is \"How much did Waugh hate his first wife to write this fictionalised version of her?\"</p><p>But perhaps the worst one of all is in The Manchurian Candidate – she is (<strong>spoiler</strong>) controlling her brainwashed son as an assassin on orders from the KGB.</p><p>At this point we sense that Sue Townsend's Adrian Mole is ready to insist that his mother Pauline should be added to the list – but I reject that totally. She is a Mother Courage for the age, spending the child benefit on gin and fags, endless boyfriends in tow, but always turning up for her children – she's a fictional mother for real mothers to relate to.</p><p>Mothers can't win – they are mean to their children, they fail to protect them from fathers, stepfathers and random new boyfriends, they are too protective, or not enough. Looking at the literature of mothers over the past 200 years, the striking thing is that the vast majority of it is written from the perspective of a child (albeit a grown-up one) and not a parent – scores to settle, grudges to chase, fair enough. It's only slowly, and in recent years, that the voice of the mother has come out – the odd middlebrow novel of the kind Virago and Persephone rescue (<a href=\"http://www.persephonebooks.co.uk/consequences.html\" title=\"\">EM Delafield</a> or <a href=\"http://www.persephonebooks.co.uk/someone-at-a-distance.html\" title=\"\">Dorothy Whipple</a>) and more recently <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/dec/16/fiction.features\" title=\"\">Margaret Drabble</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/mar/14/julie-myerson-lost-child-review\" title=\"\">Julie Myerson</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/sep/09/biography.features\" title=\"\">Rachel Cusk</a>.</p><p>But still, I'm betting there won't be much change in the proportion of bad mothers in novels. The ground is too fertile. Which are the fictional mothers you love to hate?</p>","headline":"Bad mothers in books: a literary litany","trailText":"<p>As Mother's Day looms, we are surrounded by saintly images of perfect matriarchs. But which of literature's worst mums do you prefer?</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/26/1395853403499/Brenda-Blethyn-and-Keira--006.jpg","wordcount":"1171","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-02T15:51:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/27/bad-mothers-in-books-literature","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/27/bad-mothers-in-books-literature","tags":[{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"lifeandstyle/family","webTitle":"Family","type":"keyword","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/family","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/family","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"lifea